==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Phase rule
<hw>Phase rule</hw>. <fld>(Phys. Chem.)</fld> <def>A generalization with
regard to systems of chemical equilibrium, discovered by Prof.
<person>J. Willard Gibbs</person>. It may be stated thus: <it>The degree
of variableness (number of degrees of freedom) of a system is equal to
the number of components minus the number of phases, plus two</it>.
Thus, if the components be salt and water, and the phases salt, ice,
saturated solution, and vapor, the system is invariant, that is, there
is only one set of conditions under which these four phases can exist in
equilibrium. If only three phases be considered, the system is
univariant, that is, the fixing of one condition, as temperature,
determines the others.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Phase splitter</ent>⟦br⟧
